description.narrative:
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Supporting Women Entrepreneurs in Mining Communities Project is part of Diakonia&rsquo;s Social and Economic Justice Innovation Program (SIP), financed by Sida under the frame agreement with the CivSam unit.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The project is a thematic and methodological development project, from which should benefit the selected partners. The project will be lead and planned by the partner organization the Zimbabwe Women&rsquo;s Bureau (ZWB) and implemented with support of the Zimbabwe Environmental Lawyers Association (ZELA). The goal of the project is to develop tools and strategies that inform sustainable business opportunities for women in mining communities. 
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The main objectives of the project are: 1. To develop and share with regional partner organisation a resource for systematic stakeholder engagement with the objective of promoting WIMCs business initiatives and exploiting opportunities and installing the capacity to use it, 2.To develop and share with regional partner organisations a toolkit to support and coach WIMCs in developing entrepreneurships and installing the capacity to use it, and 3.To support Diakonia partner organisations (Zimbabwe, Mali, Kenya and Zambia) in adapting to their context the resource for systematic stakeholder engagement and the toolkit to support and coach WIMCs
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The main problem being addressed is lack of relevant stakeholder engagement and entrepreneurship skills development for economic and social empowerment of women living in mining communities .Rights holders for this project mainly include women and young women living in selected mining communities .&nbsp; 
&nbsp;
